com.rafaelbattesti.jungle

Class GameExtended

  • java.lang.Object
    • logic.Game
      • com.rafaelbattesti.jungle.GameExtended
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class GameExtended
extends logic.Game
    This Class intends to define the methods to initialize a Jungle game.
    It contains a Main method that instantiates the GameExtended itself and passes it to a GameView instance.
    Since:
    2015-04-19
    Version:
    1.0
    Author:
    Rafael Battesti for Jungle Project 2015 - PROG10082 - Java 1
    See Also:

      • whoWon

        public int whoWon()
        Method that runs after every turn and checks for winning conditions.
        Winner will be declared if one of the following conditions is satisfied.
        1. Player has reached the opponent's Den.
        2. Player has captured all the opponent's Pieces.
        Overrides:
        whoWon in class logic.Game
        Returns:
        1 for Blue, -1 for Red and 0 for Continue.

      • initPieces

        public void initPieces()
        Method to initialize the pieces.
        Uses the global variable Piece[][] pieces to determine the position of the pieces on the board.

        Acts in three stages:
        1. Cleans up _blackPieces and _redPieces.
        2. Instantiates StringestPiece, WeakestPiece, StandardJunglePiece and JumpingPiece.
        3. Adds new Pieces to the _blackPieces and _redPieces ArrayLists.

        Overrides:
        initPieces in class logic.Game

      • randomMove

        public java.util.ArrayList<logic.tile.Tile> randomMove()
        Method that returns a movement in case there are no attacks or vulnerable pieces.
        It checks for "stupid" moves calling isMoveStupid(). If the only move available is stupid, it does it.
        Returns:

      • isMoveStupid

        public java.util.ArrayList<logic.tile.Tile> isMoveStupid(logic.piece.Piece piece,
                                                         java.util.ArrayList<logic.tile.Tile> possibleDestinations)
        Method to verify whether a chosen movement is "stupid", like giving away a piece on a silver platter. :-)
        It removes from the possibleDestinations <Tile> all "stupid" movements.
        In case it becomes empty, the randomMove() method will try another Piece until it finds a Piece which contains a non-stupid valid move.
        It has a recursive call to avoid ArrayOutOfBounds Exception.
        Parameters:
        piece - is the piece being tested in randomMove()
        possibleDestinations - is the ArrayList <Tile> possibleMoves for the testing Piece.
        Returns:
        ArrayList <Tile> possibleDestinations [tile1, ... , tile4]. Returns empty if all movements are "stupid".
